{{unreferenced|date=August 2017}} {{Infobox Artwork |image_file = James Abbott McNeill Whistler - Nocturne- Blue and Silver - Chelsea - Google Art Project.jpg |painting_alignment = right |title = Nocturne: Blue and Silver - Chelsea |artist = [[James Abbott McNeill Whistler]] |year = circa 1871 |medium = [[Oil painting|Oil on panel]] |height_metric = 50.2 |width_metric = 60.8 |metric_unit=cm |imperial_unit=in |city = [[London]] |museum = [[Tate Collection]] }} '''''Nocturne: Blue and Silver – Chelsea''''' is a painting. It is the earliest of the London Nocturnes by [[James McNeill Whistler]].
The work has influences from [[Asian art|Oriental art]]. The connection to [[Woodblock printing in Japan|Japanese prints]] and [[Chinese paintings]] is underscored by Whistler's use of the 'butterfly' signature in the centre of the bottom edge of the painting. {{commons category}} {{Whistler}}
